close_symbols: object_ids[] element type (e.g., uint8) and array size
OS_SUCCESS (return code) and relevant error return codes (e.g., OS_INVALID_POINTER)
explanation:
For assessing whether the bit-clear operation in OS_SelectFdClear is dead code we need symbols that determine (a) whether the operation can be reached and (b) whether removing it would change observable program behaviour. Explanations: 

- OS_FdSet (structure definition): needed to know the layout and semantics of the Set object, in particular whether modifying Set->object_ids is observable elsewhere (aliasing, volatile qualifiers, etc.).

- object_ids[] element type (e.g., uint8) and array size: needed to verify the semantics of the bit operation (width, mask correctness) and to check index/bounds — if the array is not used or has zero size the write might be dead.

- OS_CHECK_POINTER (macro/implementation): this macro is executed at function entry; it may perform logging, return early, or have side effects. Its expansion determines reachability of the rest of the function and whether the function contains observable side effects even when the bit clear is removed.

- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex (implementation/prototype): the call may have side effects (logging, state changes) beyond producing local_id. If it does, then the call itself may be the only observable effect and the bit clear could be dead or not depending on semantics. We must inspect its behaviour.

- OS_GetMaxForObjectType (used by OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex): required if OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex consults global maxima to validate/compute local_id; needed to reason about index validity and whether the computed local_id leads to an observable write.

- OS_SUCCESS and relevant error return codes (e.g., OS_INVALID_POINTER): the function branches on return_code == OS_SUCCESS; knowing the exact return values lets us reason which path executes and whether the write is ever performed.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_STREAM (constant): the object-type argument passed to OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex may change behaviour of that helper (validation, index mapping); needed to reason about whether the helper returns success and which index is produced.

- osal_index_t (typedef / range): used for local_id; its width / signedness matters for shifting, indexing and whether the write is well-defined or UB (which affects whether removal affects behaviour).

- osal_id_t (typedef / encoding): the encoding/valid ranges of objid determine how OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex maps to local_id and whether the write is relevant.

- OS_SelectFdAdd, OS_SelectFdIsSet, OS_SelectFdZero, OS_SelectMultiple, OS_SelectSingle: these other select-related functions read or manipulate the same OS_FdSet/object_ids. To determine if clearing a bit in object_ids has any externally observable effect (i.e., removing it would change program behaviour), we must see how other code reads/depends on object_ids (e.g., selection logic, tests). If no reader uses that bit, the clear is dead; if readers do, it is live.

In summary, the above symbols let the next analyst determine reachability, side-effects of the helper call, correctness/validity of the index and array access, and whether other code observes the modified state — all necessary to decide if the clear operation qualifies as dead code under MISRA C.
